\begin_layout Section
Stage 2 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Email
\series default
: "Dear XYZ, I saw that the XYZ postdoctoral fellowship is being offered
 this fall.
 I'm trying finish my thesis this spring, and was considering applying.
 I would certainly be interested in working with you--are you currently
 looking to take on any postdocs? I'd be happy to discuss further if you're
 interested."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Cover Letter
\series default
: Emphasize how your work is relevant to the goal of the postdoc, and reframe
 your work within their context of the project.
 Briefly summarize your relevant qualifications for this position.
 You want to convey how the lab or department will benefit having you there,
 rather than how you will benefit from getting this postdoc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Research Proposal
\series default
: Your research proposal explains the research you would do during the postdoc.
 You should introduce the topic while referring to past literature and point
 out the knowledge gaps in the field that your project will fill.
 Then go through your timeline of what you will accomplish (including publicatio
ns) and when.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Research statement
\series default
: Unlike the research proposal, this document goes through your previous
 research experience and includes publications, talks, conference presentations
 or posters that have come from it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
CV
\series default
: 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "click here"
target "https://academicpositions.com/career-advice/how-to-write-a-professional-academic-cv"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Recommendation
\series default
: Two or three good recommendation letters.
\end_layout

